		<p>
			Today we would call the huge number we calculated above <m>26!</m>, which is read "26 factorial," and certainly takes up a lot less room.
		</p>
		<definition xml:id="definition_factorial">
			<title> Factorial </title>
			<statement> 
				<p>
					Given a counting number <m>n</m> we define <term><m>n</m>-factorial</term><idx>factorial</idx> as the number of ways in which we can arrange <m>n</m> objects and we calculate it by taking the product of all the consecutive positive integers from <m>n</m> down to 1, and we write:
					<men>
						n!=n(n-1)(n-2)\cdots 2 \cdot 1
					</men>
					Note that for a variety of reasons <m>0!=1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>
			Thus we can make a message harder to decipher simply by using a more inventive method of encipherment.
		</p>

